@misc{Mahdi.26October2012,
 abstract = {13 October 2012



These items stick out in terms of their syllable structure and/or stress pattern. Hence, I suspect that they might be non-Malay roots. What do you think? 

giawas 'guava' 

grobak 'wheelbarrow' 

honai 'traditional.Dani hut'

kombong 'inflated'

koteka 'penis sheath' 

krempeng 'thin'

palungku or flungku 'fist' 

pakwel 'k.o. crowbar' 



Well, {\_}grobak{\_} and {\_}krempeng{\_} re definitely of (Bazaar/Ucontact) Malay origin. The standeard indonesian Malay spellings are: gerobak and kerempeng [ker{\'e}mp{\'e}ng]. 

{\_}kombong{\_} is a loaned cognate of Malay kembung (the penultimate vowel is schwa). It might be worthwhile to check whether it is from Javanese. 

{\_}palungku{\_} and {\_}pakwel{\_} are likely to be from some vernacular Malay dialect of East Indonesia, but I canot say from which. Try checking Ambon Malay for a start 

{\_}giawas{\_} is probably a loan from an ultimately Spanish plural guayabas. 

{\_}koteka{\_} is certinly, and {\_}bonai{\_} very likely to be of local indigenous origin. 



kecuali 'except' - *cuali does not exist in Papuan Malay 

The ultimate baseword is probably a no longer existent *cual probably meaning something like 'pry up, gouge out', and is affixed here with a no longer productive combination of prefix ke- and suffix -i. But this is just a speculative guess of mine. In modern Malay the word as a whole is not morphologically divisible.



keluar 'go out' - luar as well as dari/di luar do exist in Papuan Malay 

In Standard indonesian Malay there are two morphologically distinct {\_}keluar{\_}-s, the one is a combination of the proclitic {\_}ke{\_} 'to, towards' and the locative {\_}luar{\_} 'outside, external'.The other is the compound verb {\_}keluar{\_} 'go out(wards)'. The former is the antonym of {\_}ke dalam{\_}, the latter of {\_}masuk{\_}. It was not always clear, which of the two is meant in written texts, because in s{\'o}me contexts, both are possible. This only changed after the spelling reform required the former to spelled du{\'i}sunctedly as {\_}ke luar{\_}. 

But whatever the case, the ke- here is not th prefix ke-, but the (homonymixc) preposition.



keliar 'roam about' - liar 'be wild' does exist in Papuan Malay but my corpus does not include di/dari liar 

This was historically probably a derivation with profix {\_}ke-{\_}, that has meanwhile become incorporated into the word, so that on the diachri{\'o}nic plain {\_}keliar{\_} is a basic (non-derived) word.



olahraga 'do sports' - Russell lists this item as olah - raga (both parts are Malay)

Russel Jones is right. Well, the way I see it, this is a case of the classical question of whether you are preparing a treatment of the synchrony or the diachrony. The former covers affixes and root-morphemes being features of the contemporaneous language. The latter covers historical roots that are not necessarily still independent features of the morphology anymore. In the present example, the situation is even more simple, however. If as you say the word was acquired in Papuan Malay as a whole, while the substituent items in the donor Malay dialect were not acquired as well. Ror Papuan Malay then, the entire entity {\_}olahraga{\_} is morphologically indivisible 

Of course, real life can play the meanest strokes on thngs that theoretically sem so simple. Bilingual speakers who also have a substantial mastery of Standard indonesian Malay could be well aware of the etymology, even if they never use the historically basic items whe speaking the vernacular.





28 October 2012



Anyway, the source of gerobak in standard Malay is relatively obvious. it was apparently borrowed via Bazaar Malay from Javanese grobag (with final g, that excludes the likelihood of a borrowing in te reverse direction). As for ker{\'e}mp{\'e}ng, finding te source is more difficult.It does not seem to be an original item of nuclear (Riau-Johore) Malay, but is also not attested for eithr Javanese or Sundanese (also not *kerimping). I only found it in Jakarta Malay. I haven't had time to search further yet so far.},
 author = {Mahdi, Waruno},
 year = {26 October 2012},
 title = {Papuan Malay -- Some lexical roots: Are they Malay or non-Malay items? p.c.},
