@book{Haiman.1988,
 abstract = {Traditionally the study of syntax is restricted to the study of what goes on within the boundaries of the prosodic sentence. Although the nature of clause combining within a prosodic sentence has always been a central concern of traditional syntax (in GG, e.g. it underlies important research on deletion and anaphora), work within a discourse analysis framework has hardly been done. Analyses like this are given in the present volume.



This vol in the Typological Studies in Language series contains an Introduction by the editors {\&} 13 Chpts. Works adopting a discourse analysis approach to clause combining are presented. Wallace Chafe - Linking Intonation Units in Spoken English - examines linkages between intonation units in spoken discourse. Linkages may be accomplished through intonation alone, or through use of {\dq}coordinating{\dq} connectives including and, but, so, like, I mean, etc, or {\dq}subordinating{\dq} connectives. Carol Genetti - A Syntactic Correlate of Topicality in Newari Narrative - explores an alternative in the case marking of subject noun phrases in clause chains found in the narrative texts of Newari, a Tibeto-Burman language of Nepal. It is argued that the case marking alternation cannot be accounted for syntactically or semantically but must be considered as a function of discourse pragmatics. John Haiman - InconsequentialClauses in Hua and the Typology of Clauses - discusses means of expressing the meaning typically expressed by English but, in the Papuan language Hua, with emphasis on the so-called inconsequential construction. Relative distribution of the inconsequential {\&} the conditional is considered {\&} the unusual nature of grammatical categories in this language is emphasized. Martin Harris - Concessive Clauses in English and Romance - analyzes the semantics of concessive conditionals. It is argued that the concessive conditional sets up a hypothesis the realization of which, if {\&} when it occurs, would bring into existence a situation in which a particular type of concessive interpretation would be relevant. The analysis is based on a comparison of concessives in English {\&} in Romance languages. Ekkehard Konig {\&} Johan van der Auwera - Clause Integration in German and Dutch Conditionals, Concessive Conditionals, and Concessives - explores broader issues of subordination {\&} clause combining in syntax through a discussion of conditionals {\&} concessives in Dutch {\&} German. Methods of combining these constructions with a main clause are described as lying along a continuum from parataxis to embedding. Knud Lambrecht - Presentational Cleft Constructions in Spoken French - examines the avoir-cleft construction used in spoken French as a presentational construction {\&} in an {\dq}event reporting{\dq} pragmatic function. The unusual nature of the relationship between main {\&} subordinate clauses in these event reporting sentences is examined. Christian Lehmann - Towards a Typology of Clause Linkage - provides a survey of the significant aspects of complex clause formations in the languages of the world. Cross-linguistic types of clause linkage are identified. Lorna MacDonald - Subordination in Tauya - examines subordinates marked by -na in the Papuan language Tauya. Analysis centers on the inconsequential construction {\&} their pragmatic {\&} structural independence from the main clause is discussed. Lynell Marchese - Sequential Chaining and Discourse Structure in Godie - explores the sequential auxiliary in Godie, an Eastern Kru language spoken in the Ivory Coast. The syntactic {\&} discourse characteristics of its use as a chaining device are examined, {\&} speaker motivations for its use are described. Christian Matthiessen {\&} Sandra A. Thompson - The Structure of Discourse and 'Subordination' - examines the structure of discourse within which subordinate clauses appear. It is argued that characterization of the subordinate clause at the sentence level is neither desirable nor possible. A discourse model of the notion {\dq}subordinate clause{\dq} is outlined based on an evaluation of written English discourse. Marianne Mithun - The Grammaticization of Coordination - describes ways in which coordination is grammaticized in several typologically different languages. It is shown that this apparently basic device is actually highly diverse from one language to the next, but is also easily borrowed. John Myhill {\&} Junko Hibiya - The Discourse Function of Clause-Chaining - provides an empirical study of clause chaining constructions in Japanese {\&} Soddo, a Semitic language spoken in Southern Ethiopia. It is shown that these constructions are not, as has been previously claimed, associated with a foregrounding function. Johanna Nichols - Nominalization and Assertion in Scientific Russian Prose - examines the use of the Russian verbal noun in contexts where English translation uses assertion or a finite verb. The basing of the choice to use assertion or nonassertion, {\&} finite or nominalized verb form, in the grammatical category inventory of the language is described.},
