 abstract = {The word sama was borrowed from Sanskrit into Malay in ancient times with the meaning 'same'.  Much later it also came to mean 'with' in Bazaar Malay.  Based on this, a standardized form bersama '(together) with' as created in the modern language.  In Classical Malay sama only means 'same' and bersama does not occur. The reason that you don't find sama 'with' in WOLD is because the database is for standard Indonesian, and in standard Indonesian the word for 'with' is dengan.  The word bersama is not marked as a loanword because it was created in Malay be prefixng ber- to the (borrowed) base sama.  So while sama is a loanword, bersama is not.

