'Ergative-absolutive' (or simply 'ergative') languages, by minimal definition, identify noun phrase constituents in normal active, declarative surface forms as follows: the object of a transitive verb and the subject of an intransitive are treated alike, and the subject of a transitive verb is treated differently from both of these. Contrast in (I) this ergative schema A with the schema B of 'nominative-accusative' (or simply 'accusative') languages, such as the IndoEuropean languages with which we, as speakers, are familiar.},
