@misc{Paauw.2013,
 abstract = {The Malay language has been a lingua franca in insular Southeast Asia for at least a millennium, and quite likely for much longer. Trade in spices which originated in the islands of eastern Indonesia---primarily cloves and nutmeg---fed into a trade network which stretched to the Middle East and Europe centuries before Europeans first appeared in the archipelago. The language used to conduct this trade was Malay, which was used as a language of wider communication as far afield as the Philippines, New Guinea and Australia for hundreds of years. Malay was particularly well--suited for this purpose, due to its {\dq}undressed{\dq} morphology and isolating nature.

In various locations in eastern Indonesia, varieties of Malay emerged in the centuries before European contact, initially as trade languages for limited purposes, but eventually becoming the native languages of populations in these regions. These eastern Indonesian contact varieties of Malay continue to expand today, although they are under threat from regional varieties of colloquial Indonesian. A number of these varieties were well--established when Europeans first arrived in the early 16th century, and they may have existed as long as 1000 years ago (Blust 1988:8).

This study is concerned with seven of the Malay contact varieties of eastern Indonesia: Manado Malay in northern Sulawesi, North Moluccan Malay in the northern Moluccas islands, Ambon Malay and Banda Malay in the central Moluccas, Kupang Malay in western Timor island, and Papua Malay in the Indonesian half of New Guinea1(see Figure 1). These varieties have become the native languages for at least some portion of their communities, and most are also used as languages of wider communication in their regions. There are other Malay varieties in eastern Indonesia which may also fit these conditions, notably Makassar Malay and Alor Malay.},
