@misc{Blust.14October2012,
 abstract = {The following are from Malay:

giawas 'guava'

grobak 'wheelbarrow'

tiarap 'lie face downwards'



The guava is a New World plant, introduced into the Philippines by the Spanish in the 16th century (Spanish guayaba).~ Like many other Spanish nouns, it was borrowed in its plural form, as Tagalog /bayabas/.~ This then spread southward into Malay, where it underwent the regular sound change of *aba {\textgreater} -awa, to yield Malay /biawas/.~ Loanwords often show sporadic changes, and in this case it looks like the original g- went to b- and then back to g- in the borrowing process (since -w- identifies it as a form acquired through Malay).

